					<div style="margin: 0 5ex;">For those running Firefox on Windows XP for whom &#9425;, the unicode character 24D1, doesn&#039;t display properly, I have an easy fix:<br />1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Download the Quivira font from this page (http://www.quivira-font.com/).<br />2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Extract the file and install the font according to this guide (http://support.microsoft.com/kb/314960).<br />3.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In Firefox, select Tools --&gt; Options and then the Content tab. Under Fonts &amp; Colors, click the Advanced button.<br />4.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Select &#039;Other Languages&#039; in the Fonts for drop down field.<br />5.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Select &#039;Serif&#039; in the Proportional field.<br />6.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Select &#039;Quivira&#039; in both the Serif and Sans-serif fields.<br />7.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Select &#039;Western (ISO-8859-1)&#039; in the Default Character Encoding field.<br />8.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Click the &#039;OK&#039; button in the current window, and then again the next window.<br /><br />&#9425; should now display properly in your browser. If you have another font in mind that supports &#9425;, feel free to swap it for the one I suggested.<br /></div>
